\b Variables
\b0 \
There are several different data types in MATLAB . We do not have to specify the data type when declaring a variable in MATLAB. \
The different data types are listed below:\
1.Floating Point Numbers: \
Class: Single, Double\
Floating Point Number is the default data type in MATLAB. They are used to store real numbers. e.g. F = 1.89938532. \
2.Integers: Integers are of the following classes in MATLAB.  \
Class: uint8, int8, uint16, int16, uint32, int32, uint64 and int64.\

\f3 \cf5 This data type is more memory efficient and allows for storage of whole numbers. "u" stands for unsigned integers while "8,16,32,64" stand for the number of bits for storage. e.g. C = uint16(256) \

\f1\fs24 \cf2 3. Characters and Strings:Used to store text. \
Class: char\
A string is an array of characters while char signifies each one. e.g. c = \'93Hello\'94\
4.Boolean: \
class: logical \
Used to Store true(1) or false(0)\
5.Structures: \
Class: Struct\
Used to Store varying lengths of Data types. the data types are accessed using an index.\
\
Matlab is an interpreted language meaning it is dynamically compiled. It allows numerical calculations and the Visualisation of the results associated with it.\
